# 📖 Introduction

SQL provides clauses to:

- Sort data
- Display only required rows

Today we learned:

```text
✅ ORDER BY

✅ Multiple Column ORDER BY

✅ LIMIT

✅ OFFSET
```

These are very common in placement interviews.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

# 📘 ORDER BY

The **ORDER BY** clause is used to sort records.

## Syntax

```sql
SELECT *
FROM Employee
ORDER BY ColumnName;
```

Default sorting order:

```text
Ascending (ASC)
```

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

# 📘 ASC (Ascending)

Sorts data from:

```text
Small → Large

A → Z
```

Example

```sql
SELECT *
FROM Employee
ORDER BY Salary ASC;
```

Output

```text
100000

400000

400000

600000

3500000
```

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

# 📘 DESC (Descending)

Sorts data from:

```text
Large → Small

Z → A
```

Example

```sql
SELECT *
FROM Employee
ORDER BY Salary DESC;
```

Output

```text
3500000

600000

400000

400000

100000
```

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

# 📘 ORDER BY Employee Name

Example

```sql
