Ferit

Rehyan

Seyran

Suna
```

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

# 📘 ORDER BY Department

Example

```sql
SELECT *
FROM Employee
ORDER BY Department ASC;
```

Output

```text
HR

IT

Sales
```

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

# 📘 Multiple Column ORDER BY

Sometimes one column contains duplicate values.

Example

```text
Seyran = 400000

Rehyan = 400000
```

We can sort using more than one column.

## Syntax

```sql
SELECT *
FROM Employee
ORDER BY Department ASC, Salary DESC;
```

Meaning

```text
First

↓

Department

↓

If Departments are same

↓

Sort Salary in Descending Order
```

Output

```text
HR

Suna

600000

↓

Rehyan

400000

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

IT

Ferit

3500000

↓

Seyran

400000

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Sales

Emir
```

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

# 📘 LIMIT

The **LIMIT** clause restricts the number of rows returned.

## Syntax

```sql
SELECT *
FROM Employee
LIMIT 3;
```

Output

```text
First 3 Rows
```

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

# 📘 Top 3 Highest Paid Employees

```sql
SELECT *
FROM Employee
ORDER BY Salary DESC
LIMIT 3;
```

Output

```text
Ferit

Suna

Seyran
```

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

# 📘 Highest Paid Employee

```sql
